# Python Project Rules

## Naming Conventions
- Methods, functions, and variables: snake_case
- Classes: PascalCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Private methods and attributes: prefix with a single underscore
- File names: snake_case, and the file name should match the primary class it contains

## Data Model Implementation
- All data models (Transaction, Budget) should use dataclass implementation
- Validation should be implemented in `__post_init__` methods
- All classes must have docstrings explaining their purpose
- All methods must have Google-style docstrings with description, parameters (Args), and return values (Returns)
- All method and function parameters must have type hints, and all methods and functions must have return type annotations

## Object-Oriented Programming
- Follow OOP best practices: use classes with clear responsibilities, encapsulation, and separation of concerns
- Each class should have a single responsibility — do not create classes that manage unrelated concerns
- Use private attributes (prefixed with underscore) for internal state that should not be accessed directly
- Prefer dependency injection — pass dependencies into a class rather than creating them internally

## Documentation and Type Hints
- All functions and methods must have Google-style docstrings with a description, parameters (Args), and return values (Returns)
- All classes must have a docstring explaining their purpose
- Use inline comments to explain non-obvious logic — but do not over-comment obvious code
- All method and function parameters must have type hints, and all methods and functions must have return type annotations
- Use Sphinx as the primary documentation generation tool for Python projects
- Documentation must be generated from docstrings following Google-style format
- API documentation should be automatically built and published (e.g., to GitHub Pages or Read the Docs)
- Include auto-generated API reference documentation for all public modules, classes, and functions
- Documentation should include usage examples and code snippets
- Generate both HTML and PDF documentation formats
- Documentation must be versioned and updated with each release
- Include a documentation build process in the CI pipeline
- User documentation must be appended to README.md after each phase of implementation
- Documentation should include project overview, installation instructions, and usage examples
- Include clear installation steps and prerequisites
- Add troubleshooting sections for common issues
- Document configuration options and environment variables
- Provide API documentation in the README for public interfaces

## Logging and Error Handling
- Use Python's standard logging module for all application logging
- Configure logging with appropriate log levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL)
- Log messages should be informative but not verbose
- Include contextual information in log messages (user IDs, request IDs, etc.)
- Log to appropriate destinations (console, files, external services)
- Use structured logging for better parsing and analysis
- Implement log rotation to prevent disk space issues
- Log exceptions with full stack traces for debugging
- Use specific exception types rather than generic exceptions
- Catch exceptions at the appropriate level in the call stack
- Always log exceptions with sufficient context for debugging
- Implement proper exception propagation for meaningful error reporting
- Use try/except/finally blocks appropriately
- Don't ignore exceptions silently
- Create custom exceptions for application-specific error conditions
- Handle expected error conditions gracefully with user-friendly messages
- All exceptions should be logged with appropriate severity levels
- Include relevant context information when raising exceptions
- Use exception chaining to preserve original error information
- Implement centralized error handling for API endpoints
- Provide meaningful error messages to users without exposing internal details
- Log security-related exceptions (authentication failures, authorization errors)
- Implement application health checks
- Monitor application performance and resource usage
- Set up alerts for critical errors and system failures
- Log application startup and shutdown events
- Track important business events and user actions
- Implement circuit breaker patterns for external service calls
- Never log sensitive information (passwords, tokens, personal data)
- Sanitize log output to remove PII before logging
- Implement proper access controls for log files
- Use encrypted logging for sensitive applications
- Implement log auditing for compliance requirements
- Include error handling in unit tests
- Test that appropriate exceptions are raised for invalid inputs
- Verify that error messages are user-friendly and informative
- Test exception handling paths in integration tests
- Ensure error recovery mechanisms work correctly

## Security Best Practices
- All user inputs must be validated before processing
- Implement both client-side and server-side validation
- Use whitelisting for allowed input values where possible
- Validate data types, lengths, and formats of all inputs
- Sanitize input data to prevent injection attacks
- Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse of input endpoints
- Never use eval() or similar dangerous functions
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement proper authentication and authorization mechanisms
- Use secure password hashing (bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2)
- Implement secure session management
- Use HTTPS/TLS for all network communications
- Encrypt sensitive data at rest using industry-standard encryption
- Use secure random number generation for cryptographic operations
- Implement proper access controls and least privilege principles
- Regularly audit and review security configurations
- Implement data loss prevention measures
- Use secure file upload handling with proper validation
- Implement multi-factor authentication where appropriate
- Use secure token management (JWT, OAuth, etc.)
- Implement proper session timeout and invalidation
- Use role-based access control (RBAC) for sensitive operations
- Implement secure password policies and account lockout mechanisms
- Include security scanning in CI pipeline
- Perform regular vulnerability assessments
- Implement security testing as part of the testing strategy
- Include penetration testing for critical applications
- Use automated security tools for static and dynamic analysis
- Regular security training for development team members
- Never log sensitive information (passwords, tokens, personal data) - this is already covered above
- Sanitize log output to remove PII before logging - this is already covered above
- Implement proper error handling that doesn't expose internal details
- Log security-related events (failed logins, access attempts)
- Implement alerting for security incidents
- Use structured logging for security event analysis
- Regularly update and patch all dependencies
- Monitor for security vulnerabilities in third-party libraries
- Implement dependency verification and validation
- Use trusted sources for all dependencies
- Implement security scanning for all code dependencies
- Maintain an inventory of all third-party components
- Follow OWASP Top 10 security guidelines
- Implement security by design principles
- Comply with relevant data protection regulations (GDPR, CCPA, etc.)
- Maintain security documentation and policies
- Implement incident response procedures
- Regular security assessments and compliance reviews

## Formatting
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Maximum line length: 88 characters
- Imports ordered: standard library first, then third-party, then local — with a blank line between each group
- Maximum cyclomatic complexity for functions should not exceed 10
- Functions with complexity above 10 should be refactored into smaller, more manageable pieces
- Maximum lines per function should not exceed 30 lines
- Functions should be small and focused on a single responsibility
- If a function exceeds 30 lines, it should be broken down into smaller functions
- Maximum lines per class should not exceed 100 lines
- Classes should have a single responsibility and not become "god objects"
- Maximum lines per file should not exceed 300 lines
- Maximum nested if/else statements should be 2 levels deep
- Maximum nested loops should be 2 levels deep
- Complex conditional logic should be extracted into separate functions
- Use early returns to reduce nesting levels
- Code should be readable and maintainable
- Complex logic should be documented with comments
- Refactoring should be done proactively rather than reactively
- Code reviews should consider complexity as part of the evaluation

## Project Structure
- All source code goes in the src/ directory
- All tests go in the tests/ directory
- Data files go in the data/ directory
- No executable code at module level except inside an if __name__ == "__main__" guard
- Use pyproject.toml as the primary dependency management file for new projects
- Maintain requirements.txt for compatibility with legacy systems or specific deployment needs
- All dependencies must be explicitly versioned with appropriate version constraints
- Pin exact versions for production dependencies to ensure reproducible builds
- Use semantic versioning ranges for development dependencies where appropriate
- Document dependency rationale in comments for major libraries
- Separate dependencies into categories: Production, Development, Optional
- Group dependencies by purpose in pyproject.toml
- Keep dependency lists sorted alphabetically for easier maintenance
- Regular dependency updates should be monitored and tested
- Security scanning tools should be integrated into CI pipeline
- Critical security vulnerabilities must be addressed within 2 weeks
- Dependency version updates should follow semantic versioning principles
- Outdated dependencies should be flagged in CI pipeline
- Use tools like pip-audit or dependabot for automated security checks
- Use virtual environments for all development work
- Include dependency installation instructions in README.md
- Provide a standard command for installing all dependencies (e.g., `make install`)
- Document how to add new dependencies to the project
- Specify minimum Python version requirements
- All dependencies must be tested in development environment
- CI pipeline should verify that dependencies install correctly
- Include dependency validation in pre-commit hooks
- Test with different Python versions if applicable
- Verify that all dependencies are compatible with each other
- Document dependency management process in CONTRIBUTING.md
- Include dependency management best practices in developer onboarding
- Specify how to add new dependencies to the project
- Document the process for removing unused dependencies
- Include information about dependency licensing requirements
- Provide guidance on when to use pip vs poetry vs other tools
- Use environment variables for configuration that varies between environments
- Follow a consistent naming convention for environment variables (UPPER_SNAKE_CASE)
- Document all required environment variables in README.md
- Include default values for optional environment variables where appropriate
- Never hardcode sensitive information like passwords or API keys in source code
- Use environment variable validation to ensure required values are present
- Use configuration files (e.g., config.yaml, config.json) for complex application settings
- Support multiple configuration file formats (YAML, JSON, TOML) based on project needs
- Organize configuration files by environment (development, staging, production)
- Include configuration file examples in the repository with default values
- Implement a centralized configuration loading mechanism
- Support configuration file fallback to environment variables
- Validate configuration at application startup
- Provide clear error messages for missing or invalid configuration values
- Use type conversion for configuration values to ensure proper data types
- Never commit sensitive configuration files to version control
- Use .gitignore to exclude configuration files containing secrets
- Implement configuration encryption for sensitive data in production
- Use secure configuration management tools for production environments
- Rotate secrets regularly and update configurations accordingly
- Include example configuration files (with dummy values) in the repository
- Provide clear instructions for setting up local development configuration
- Document the difference between development, staging, and production configurations
- Include configuration validation in CI pipeline
- Support configuration overrides for testing environments
- Include configuration testing in unit tests
- Document all configuration options in README.md
- Include examples of configuration files for different environments
- Explain the purpose and expected values for each configuration parameter
- Provide guidance on when to use environment variables vs configuration files
- Include troubleshooting tips for common configuration issues

## Quality Assurance
- All code must pass ruff check and ruff format with no errors
- All code must pass mypy with no type errors
- Run these checks before considering any task complete
- CI pipeline must run automated testing, linting, and type checking on every push
- All code must pass all automated tests before merging to main branch
- CI pipeline must run ruff check and ruff format on all Python files
- CI pipeline must run mypy type checking on all Python files
- Linting and type checking errors must block PR merging until resolved
- CI pipeline must enforce code quality standards automatically
- Security scanning must be performed in CI pipeline
- Build and deployment automation must be part of CI pipeline
- Pipeline must generate and publish test reports and coverage statistics
- CI pipeline must track build success/failure metrics
- Main branch should be protected with required status checks
- Pull requests must pass all CI checks before merging
- Code review standards must be enforced for all pull requests
- Minimum 1 reviewer required for code changes
- Code reviews must check for security issues and vulnerabilities
- Code reviews must verify adherence to all project coding standards
- Pull requests must be approved by at least one reviewer before merging
- Critical security changes require additional security reviewer approval
- Code review process should include checking for proper documentation updates
- Code review checklist should include testing coverage verification
- Code review process should verify dependency updates and security implications

## Testing Conventions
- Use pytest as the primary testing framework
- Test files must be named test_<module>.py and mirror the source structure (e.g., src/storage.py maps to tests/test_storage.py)
- Test functions must be named test_<what_it_does>_<expected_outcome> (e.g., test_add_contact_with_empty_name_raises_error)
- Each test must be independent — no test should depend on another test's state or execution order
- Tests must cover happy path, error cases, and relevant boundary conditions
- Write tests alongside the code, as part of the same task — a task is not complete until its tests exist and pass
- All tests must be runnable with `pytest` command
- Minimum 80% code coverage (statement coverage) with coverage reports generated
- Coverage reports must be published (e.g., to codecov or similar)
- Critical business logic should have 100% coverage
- Integration tests should cover major user flows
- Tests must pass before any code can be merged to main branch
- CI pipeline should run all tests with coverage reporting
- Local development should support running tests with `make test` or similar
- Include a script to run tests with coverage: `make test-coverage`
- Support for running specific test files or test functions
- All tests must be deterministic and not rely on external state
- Tests should run in isolation (no test dependencies)
- Use mocking for external dependencies (API calls, databases, file I/O)
- Include performance tests for critical functions
- Generate HTML coverage reports
- Include test execution time monitoring
- Provide clear failure messages that help identify root causes
- Support for junitxml output for CI integration
- Remove or update tests when code is refactored
- Add tests for bug fixes
- Regular review of test suite for redundancy or inefficiency
- Document test assumptions and edge cases
- Include performance tests for critical functions that are performance-sensitive
- Establish baseline performance benchmarks for key operations
- Document expected performance thresholds for core functionality
- Run benchmarks as part of CI pipeline for regression detection
- Include performance testing for database operations, API calls, and computational intensive functions
- Define key performance metrics (response time, throughput, memory usage)
- Include performance reporting in CI pipeline results
- Set up alerts for performance regressions beyond acceptable thresholds
- Test with realistic data sizes and volumes
- Monitor performance trends over time
